<div id="review_70181878" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/70181878" />
    <a title="liirogue" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/334806-liirogue"><img alt="liirogue" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1191105513p2/334806.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/70181878?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="liirogue" class="user" itemprop="url" name="liirogue" href="/user/show/334806-liirogue">liirogue</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer70181878" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3217999983226363848">Very disappointing. One of the things I enjoy most about reading historical fiction is being immersed in worlds of the past. Moran fails completely at this, she was never able to bring Ancient Egypt alive.<br/><br/>After thinking on this for a little bit, I think was really bothered me was the theme of the book - you are never good enough for the man you love, you have to change into something you aren&apos;t. The main character starts out beautiful, smart, speaks 6 or 7 languages, and is best friends with the</span>
  <span id="freeText3217999983226363848" style="display:none">Very disappointing. One of the things I enjoy most about reading historical fiction is being immersed in worlds of the past. Moran fails completely at this, she was never able to bring Ancient Egypt alive.<br /><br />After thinking on this for a little bit, I think was really bothered me was the theme of the book - you are never good enough for the man you love, you have to change into something you aren't. The main character starts out beautiful, smart, speaks 6 or 7 languages, and is best friends with the future pharaoh of Egypt. But that isn't good enough to snare this good friend as a husband - she must completely remake herself into something even more beautiful and perfect. She must never complain to him, she must always be polite and gracious, she must always dress to the nines. Only by becoming something completely different can she find true love.<br /><br />And this wonderful story line is set against a blah, cookie-cutter background.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3217999983226363848" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


